6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Binance uses traditional order book mechanics with funding rates calculated based on premium/discount to spot markets every 8 hours. GMX operates with oracle-based pricing and charges borrowing fees hourly based on utilization of the GLP pool. Binance rates fluctuate with market sentiment and open interest imbalances, while GMX rates are more predictable based on pool utilization metrics. GMX's hourly settlement provides more frequent arbitrage opportunities but requires active monitoring."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which platform offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Binance typically offers better opportunities due to deeper liquidity and more volatile funding rates. However, GMX's hourly settlements can provide more frequent but smaller arbitrage windows."},{"question":"How do the settlement mechanisms differ between Binance and GMX?","answer":"Binance uses traditional order book matching with 8-hour funding settlements, while GMX uses oracle pricing with hourly borrowing fees. This affects both execution quality and arbitrage timing strategies."},{"question":"What are the main risks when arbitraging between these platforms?","answer":"Key risks include Binance's potential withdrawal delays during volatility, GMX's oracle dependency, and the bridge risks when moving assets between CEX and Arbitrum. Smart contract risk is also present with GMX."},{"question":"Which platform is more cost-effective for funding rate strategies?","answer":"Binance is generally more cost-effective with lower trading fees, especially for BNB holders. GMX's higher fees can erode profits on smaller positions, but gas efficiency on Arbitrum helps offset some costs."}]}]
